    <%# SEO Article Content %>
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Biological Age Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        This biological age calculator estimates how old your body is compared to your chronological age based on six key lifestyle factors. Enter your actual age, then provide information about your exercise habits, sleep patterns, diet quality, stress levels, smoking status, and BMI. The calculator instantly computes your biological age, shows the year adjustment from each factor, and provides personalized recommendations for the areas where you have the most room for improvement.
      </p>
      <p>
        Biological age is a concept that reflects the actual condition of your body and cells rather than simply how many years you have been alive. Two people who are both 45 years old chronologically may have very different biological ages based on their lifestyle choices, genetics, and environmental exposures. This calculator focuses on the modifiable lifestyle factors that research has shown to have the greatest impact on how quickly or slowly the body ages.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Understanding the Biological Age Factors</h2>

      <h3>Exercise and Physical Activity</h3>
      <p>
        Regular physical activity is one of the most powerful anti-aging interventions available. Research consistently shows that people who exercise regularly have longer telomeres (the protective caps on chromosomes that shorten with age), better cardiovascular health, and reduced inflammation. This calculator awards the maximum benefit of minus 3 years for those exercising more than 5 hours per week, and adds 1 year for those exercising less than 1 hour per week.
      </p>

      <h3>Sleep Quality and Duration</h3>
      <p>
        Sleep is when the body performs critical maintenance and repair functions at the cellular level. Adults who consistently get 7 to 9 hours of quality sleep per night show better cognitive function, immune response, and metabolic health. Both too little sleep (under 6 hours) and too much sleep (over 9 hours) are associated with accelerated aging, which is why both extremes add 2 years in this calculator. The optimal range of 7 to 9 hours subtracts 1 year.
      </p>

      <h3>Diet Quality</h3>
      <p>
        Nutrition plays a fundamental role in cellular health and aging. A diet rich in whole foods, fruits, vegetables, lean proteins, and healthy fats provides the antioxidants, vitamins, and minerals needed to combat oxidative stress and inflammation — two primary drivers of aging. An excellent diet (rated 5) can subtract up to 3 years from biological age, while a very poor diet (rated 1) can add up to 3 years.
      </p>

      <h3>Stress Management</h3>
      <p>
        Chronic stress accelerates aging through multiple pathways including elevated cortisol levels, increased inflammation, and shortened telomeres. Very low stress subtracts 2 years while very high stress adds 4 years — making stress one of the most impactful factors in this model. Effective stress management techniques such as meditation, deep breathing, therapy, and regular social connection can significantly reduce the aging effects of stress.
      </p>

      <h3>Smoking</h3>
      <p>
        Smoking is the single largest controllable risk factor for accelerated aging, which is why it carries the heaviest penalty of plus 5 years. Tobacco smoke damages DNA, accelerates telomere shortening, promotes chronic inflammation, and impairs virtually every organ system. The good news is that quitting smoking at any age produces measurable health benefits, and much of the damage can be partially reversed over time.
      </p>

      <h3>Body Mass Index</h3>
      <p>
        Maintaining a healthy BMI (18.5 to 24.9) is associated with lower risks of chronic disease and reduced biological aging. Both underweight and overweight or obese BMI ranges carry health risks that can accelerate aging. A normal BMI subtracts 1 year, while obesity (BMI 30+) adds 3 years due to its association with chronic inflammation, insulin resistance, and increased disease risk.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>What is biological age?</h3>
      <p>
        Biological age is an estimate of how old your body appears to be based on various health and lifestyle factors, as opposed to your chronological age (how many years you have been alive). Someone with healthy habits may have a biological age younger than their chronological age, while unhealthy habits can make a person's body age faster.
      </p>

      <h3>How is biological age calculated?</h3>
      <p>
        This calculator uses a point-based system that adjusts your chronological age based on key lifestyle factors: exercise frequency, sleep quality, diet quality, stress levels, smoking status, and BMI. Each factor adds or subtracts years from your chronological age based on scientific research linking these factors to aging and longevity.
      </p>

      <h3>Can I lower my biological age?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes, biological age is modifiable through lifestyle changes. Regular exercise (3-5+ hours per week), adequate sleep (7-9 hours), a high-quality diet rich in whole foods, effective stress management, not smoking, and maintaining a healthy BMI can all contribute to lowering your biological age. Many people see improvements within months of adopting healthier habits.
      </p>

      <h3>What lifestyle factor has the biggest impact on biological age?</h3>
      <p>
        Smoking has one of the largest single impacts, adding up to 5 years to biological age. High stress levels can add up to 4 years, poor diet up to 3 years, and inadequate sleep or exercise can each add 1-2 years. Conversely, optimal exercise habits can subtract up to 3 years, and an excellent diet can subtract up to 3 years.
      </p>

      <h3>How accurate is a biological age calculator?</h3>
      <p>
        This calculator provides a simplified estimate based on well-established lifestyle risk factors. Clinical biological age tests use biomarkers such as DNA methylation, telomere length, and blood markers for more precise measurements. This tool is best used as a motivational and educational guide to identify areas for lifestyle improvement, not as a clinical diagnostic tool.
      </p>

